        "created_at": "2025-09-04T21:36:34.101Z",
        "cooked": "<p>At high zoom most messengers are extremely cramped; Signal also suffers from this issue.</p>\n<p>For users with low vision (e.g., my elderly grandfather) hiding the GIF button from the message text box would give more room to see what has been typed.</p>\n<p>I think most UX designers would agree if you crank up the zoom level, the Emoji/GIF/Sticker button is no longer worth the immense amount of space it takes up. You have space for one word per line because of the number of UI elements squeezing the text area from the left and right. The Emoji/GIF/Sticker button is the easiest thing to reorganize into the plus.</p>\n<p>For high zoom levels, it might actually make more sense to assume the text area is going to be at least two lines long and move the plus button ontop of the send button as well. This would give considerably more screen real estate back to the message being typed.</p>\n<p>It may even make sense to hidden the buttons when not composing a message, then stack all three buttons vertically on the right independent of the text area, something like:</p>\n<pre><code class=\"lang-auto\">G = GIF\n+ = +\nS = Send\n_ = message area\nT = text area\nX = wasted space\n</code></pre>\n<pre><code class=\"lang-auto\">______\n_____G\n_____+\nTTTTTS\n</code></pre>\n<p>with enough text that becomes something like:</p>\n<pre><code class=\"lang-auto\">______\nTTTTTG\nTTTTT+\nTTTTTS\n</code></pre>\n<p>which is a huge improvement over:</p>\n<pre><code class=\"lang-auto\">______\nXTTTXX\nXTTTXX\nGTTT+S\n</code></pre>",
